ntary sources, her analysis demonstrates that threats and practices can vary not only between authoritarian regimes but also within them, either over time or across different military units. The result is a persuasive explanation of otherwise puzzling behavior by authoritarian militaries. The Dictator’s Army offers a vital practical tool for those seeking to assess the likely course, costs, and outcomes of future conflicts involving nondemocratic adversaries, allies, or coalition partners.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aAuthoritarianism. 0aIran-Iraq War, 1980-1988xPolitical aspects. 0aMilitary policyxDecision making. 0aPolitics and war. 0aVietnam War, 1961-1975xPolitical aspects. 4aHistory. 4aMilitary History.  aauthoritarian military, authoritarian regime, battlefield, battlefield effectiveness, battlefield performance, military organizational practices, threat environments, military power, foreign policy, policymaking, political science.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170176440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501701764423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501701764/original  a978-3-11-060674-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles